label chapter15:

    # [Scene: Old Docks Community Hub | Morning — hours after the leak]

    scene bg ch12_f7128a_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Rapid percussive strings, bright brass stabs weaving into a driving ostinato]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Shutter clicks, murmured questions, the fizz of a broadcast drone hovering outside; distant gulls cry over rising tide]
    "You wake to the sound of your own name ricocheting — not whispered, but shouted across static and headlines. Your phone is a small, hot thing in your palm: push alerts, the city feed, a tense string of DMs. You taste salt and coffee and adrenaline."
    "Nora moves like a person who has already decided where to put her hands. Her overalls are flecked with mud; she’s balancing a DW-press pack and a battery case. Samir sits on a low crate, one"
    "boot extended, watching the room with calm that’s been earned over decades of storm. The community has gathered — volunteers folding tarps, elders whispering, teenagers chalking timelines on plywood."
    "You breathe in the smell of wet canvas and seaweed; the Hub smells like work and the day after a storm. Outside, someone has tied a handmade sign to the rail: TRUTH IS A SHORELINE. It flaps hard in the wind."

    "Reporter" "Maya Ortega, can you tell us — did you authorize the release?"
    "You can feel the current of attention align on you, hot and immediate. The leak—your leak—has already staggered the city. Data files, internal memos, and project timelines are splashed across feeds in tidy, cruel graphics. Your"
    "hand wants to hide the notebook at your hip, that battered thing that used to be private."
    show nora_daz at left:
        zoom 0.7

    nora_daz "We didn't leak to hurt anyone. We leaked because coverups hurt people more than messy honesty ever could."
    "You listen while your words find shape in someone else's mouth. Samir stands and crosses the room to the chalkboard where a timeline has been scrawled in hurried chalk. He draws a line for what was"
    "proposed and a line for what the leak revealed. The contrast is sharp and ugly and necessary."
    show samir_qureshi at right:
        zoom 0.7

    samir_qureshi "You did right by the marsh, by the kids who fish, by the roofs that still hold our history."
    "You want to tell him you were afraid to choose, that the pen in your hand trembled. He catches your eye and nods once, as if he’d felt that tremor too. The Hub hums with phone"
    "calls — allies calling offers of support, neighbors calling, offers of boats for immediate reinforcement, local legal clinics pledging to file emergency motions."

    menu:
        "Step forward and speak":
            "You step into the spill of light, voice steady. You lay out what you released—what decisions were made in corridors and how they would have cut the marsh off from the people who live on it."
        "Let Nora speak for you":
            "You nod. Nora takes the mic with a steady shoulder, and her words land like mortar—practical, precise, human. You feel the room brace as the truth becomes a communal thing."

    # --- merge ---
    "Continue"
    "Samir presses his palms together in the front row and watches you, a tide of expectation rolling through his bowed head. The gallery leans forward. You feel your ribs ache with the sudden weight of responsibility — not just legal but moral and communal."
    # [Scene: Salt Marsh Reserve | Midday — the spill of sunlight after a storm]
    hide nora_daz
    hide samir_qureshi

    scene bg ch12_f7128a_2 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: High-energy strings overlaying a steady drum; a chorus of hopeful voices underlining a rising cadence]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The slap of boots in mud, the soft crush of reeds, distant city hum like a contained storm]
    "You stand with both hands deep in mud and the taste of it at the corner of your mouth. The leak has turned the tide of public sympathy; emergency volunteers are arriving from neighborhoods across the"
    "city. People you didn't expect are here: students with emergency grants, a small platoon from a university lab carrying native grass plugs, and old fishermen with hands like carved wood who hum as they drive stakes"
    "into the soft earth."
    show nora_daz at left:
        zoom 0.7

    nora_daz "We need to reinforce the lower bank! Pass the jute rolls!"
    "You move through the line. Your sleeves are heavy with wet; the bracelet at your wrist, from the marsh elders, rubs against your skin—its woven pattern a tiny map of commitments. You realize with a sharp,"
    "bright clarity that what you exposed did not create the need; it revealed an already-present one that had been dressed in glossy renderings."
    "A young volunteer brushes mud across your palm and laughs, a sound like wind through sugarcane. Your chest opens in a way that is both furious and tender. The leak didn't make the harm; it made the harm visible—and visible things demand new hands."
    show samir_qureshi at right:
        zoom 0.7

    samir_qureshi "This is what shelter looks like when you make it together."
    "You think of the cost: your phone buzzing with polite declines from panels, emails with 'regret' and 'reconsidered' from foundations, and a formal letter from a consortium rescinding an offer because the scandal has shifted risk"
    "assessments. Your career ledger will bear new columns; they are narrow but honest. You feel the pinch—gateways closing—but in the marsh, with the work and the buzz of people, those losses feel like tolls paid for"
    "a larger crossing."

    menu:
        "Stay to finish the day in the marsh":
            "You wipe mud off your hands and sink deeper into the work. Each sapling you plant feels like a small insistence that the place will continue. You are physically exhausted but calm in purpose."
        "Return to the Hub to coordinate legal help":
            "You say a quick word to Samir and push yourself back toward the Hub. The adrenaline snaps your breath into sharp organization; you are needed to make the legal scaffolding hold."

    # --- merge ---
    "Continue"
    "Nora finds you by the planting line and takes a breath that smells of salt and sun. Her eyes are bright."

    nora_daz "We can do this without being asked. But we're going to need lawyers and a place to stash the funds we have. You did this, you know the documents. Will you lead?"
    show maya_ortega at center:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_ortega "I already started. There are copies in my cloud and in the old server Nora set up. We'll file them with the community legal clinic first."

    nora_daz "Good. Then you'll be the one who keeps us honest."
    "You laugh, the sound cracking into something like relief. The marsh accepts you back as one of its people — fingers in mud, decisions weighed against the living shoreline. The leak has spun a storm of attention; here, small steady hands turn that wind into scaffolding."
    # [Scene: Municipal Green Atrium | Afternoon — Emergency Hearing]
    hide nora_daz
    hide samir_qureshi
    hide maya_ortega

    scene bg ch12_f7128a_3 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Orchestral surge—brass and strings in triumphant counterpoint; percussion is urgent, relentless]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Microphones popping, murmurs, the scratch of pen on legal pads; the building hums with the electricity of accountability]
    "The room smells like too much coffee and cheap soap; the sunlight through the atrium glass throws long, white rectangles across the crowd. The leak has forced the council to act—in real time, emergency ordinances are"
    "drafted in the margins of binders, lawyers whisper into sleeves. Councilwoman Elena Reyes presides with that polished pragmatism you remember from prior hearings; she looks tired and fierce in equal measure."
    show councilwoman_elena_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    councilwoman_elena_reyes "This hearing is called to address revelations that concern the integrity of municipal contracting and the protection of neighborhoods under imminent risk."
    "Ari Nakamura stands beside a projection of the proposed seawall, immaculate in their blazer, AR cuff blinking. They carry the calm competence of someone who has spent a career making big things look inevitable. But even Ari Nakamura's posture is tight now; the leak has flattened the narrative of inevitability."
    show ari_nakamura at right:
        zoom 0.7

    ari_nakamura "Our firm—my firm—has always maintained that our projects are designed to protect. We contest some characterizations, but we are prepared to submit to oversight."
    "Samir presses his palms together in the front row and watches you, a tide of expectation rolling through his bowed head. The gallery leans forward. You feel your ribs ache with the sudden weight of responsibility — not just legal but moral and communal."
    show maya_ortega at center:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_ortega "The documents we released show choices made without community counsel, with displacement implied in the renderings and funding strings that would have traded people's homes for a polished coastline. We asked for partnership and were given a timeline."

    councilwoman_elena_reyes "Ms. Ortega, are you proposing specific remedies?"

    maya_ortega "We need three things today. Immediate emergency protections for any households at risk during construction; binding oversight with community seats and veto power over relocation decisions; and an independent audit into project influence and procurement practices."
    "The room reacts with a mixture of murmurs and applause. The brass crescendos inside you. Elena consults a tablet; the city charter is ancient but flexible in crisis."

    councilwoman_elena_reyes "I won't pretend this is simple. But these demands are not unreasonable, and they are urgent. I will move an emergency ordinance to: halt any procurement pending an independent review, set aside rapid-response shelter funding, and create a community oversight board with binding review authority."
    "Gasps and then a roar — some thin with disbelief, others thick with relief. The hearing tilts. Ari Nakamura watches you with an expression that is something rawer than calculation: a flicker of something like regret. They step down toward the lectern, voice even."

    ari_nakamura "Ms. Ortega, I— We did not intend to erase the neighborhood. If our documents read that way, then we failed in communicating safeguards. My firm will submit to the audit."
    "The moment is electric. You could feel the public attention as a current; it flows through your bones. Ari Nakamura looks at you, not as an adversary but as someone who has stripped away the sheen of a career-made narrative and insisted on getting messy."

    ari_nakamura "You made it visible. That was necessary."
    "You and Ari Nakamura exchange a gaze that carries an old history of peerage and competition, threaded now with a new, fragile recognition. The hearing pivots—what could have become a wave of scapegoating becomes legislation. Emergency resources are pledged; community seats are formalized; oversight is insisted upon with teeth."
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Reaches a climactic apex—cymbals crash into ringing strings and a choir-like wash of consonant harmonies]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A collective exhale that feels like a held breath finally released]
    "There are consequences you can already feel in the marrow: calls you won't receive from foundations, panels that will look at the 'risk profile' and keep their letters strictly polite. There are offers rescinded and warm"
    "introductions that have gone cold. Your career line shortens at the edges. But the atrium is alight with something else—collective agency, a legal architecture that will force the city to honor people, not just plans. The"
    "neighborhood keeps its rituals, its markets, its stories."
    "Ari Nakamura lingers near the exit. When you approach, the space between you is full of all the unspoken equations both professional and personal."

    ari_nakamura "If oversight is what it takes for me to be trusted, tell me how to help. I'm willing to be audited. I want to help rebuild… in a way that doesn't erase you."

    maya_ortega "Help means letting the community set the baseline. No more glossy renderings without us. No displacement as a cost."

    ari_nakamura "Agreed. And—' [a pause, the human crack that undercuts perfection] '—if there is anything we can do to support the repair work, we'll offer technical resources, pro bono, under oversight."
    "You let the offer stand and know you will parse it later with lawyers and elders. For now, the tide of public will is moving in the direction you fought for."
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Orchestral surge resolves into a warm, sustaining cadence]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The murmur of the crowd, distant footsteps, the rustle of paperwork]
    # [Scene: Old Docks Community Hub | Evening — Aftermath and Closure]
    hide councilwoman_elena_reyes
    hide ari_nakamura
    hide maya_ortega

    scene bg ch12_f7128a_4 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Gentle, warm strings, a low choir of voices humming; rhythmic hand-drums keep a steady pulse]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Laughter, the clink of mugs, distant gulls settling; the low murmur of a community breathing easier]
    "The day collapses into a long, warm after-breath. Volunteers trade stories and call-out notes; someone starts an old sea chanty and half the room joins. You sit on the edge of a crate with Samir, a mug warming your hands."
    show samir_qureshi at left:
        zoom 0.7

    samir_qureshi "You did dangerous work. You took risk for the neighborhood. People will talk about the leak in history. They'll call it reckless or brave; doesn't matter what the loud mouths say. The marsh and the people will remember."
    show maya_ortega at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_ortega "I lost opportunities today. Invitations retracted. Panels won't ask me. Funding doors will have closed their hinges."

    samir_qureshi "But your people keep their homes. Their markets stay. Their rituals—' (he taps the bracelet at your wrist) '—are intact. There's a kind of wealth that doesn't go on balance sheets."
    "Nora slides into the crate beside you, her hair threaded with mud and gold light. She grins, exhausted and luminous."
    show nora_daz at center:
        zoom 0.7

    nora_daz "We have less money, more work, and every reason to keep going. Also, someone from a local university promised to train two of us in low-cost monitoring tech."
    "You laugh and it breaks something tight in your chest. There is loss, yes. Practical doors have closed. But the work you are left with is yours in a way no grant can fully buy: messy,"
    "sustained, communal. You will sleep less; you will rise to fewer accolades. You will earn small satisfactions—children pointing to new reeds and naming them, elders reclaiming dock spaces, the slow return of fish to beds you"
    "helped rebuild."
    "Ari Nakamura returns with two steaming bowls, hands slightly rougher than their tailored image suggested. They hand one to you."
    hide samir_qureshi
    show ari_nakamura at left:
        zoom 0.7

    ari_nakamura "I said I would help. I'm not sure how you'll take help from the firm, and that's fair. But—' (a beat) '—I can teach permit-skills to residents, help set up monitoring frameworks, and I'll push for the oversight board to have actual power."

    maya_ortega "Then show up here, not at a podium. Roll up your sleeves."

    ari_nakamura "I'll bruise my cuffs."
    "You share a laugh that is both real and a little shaky. There's an intimacy in the shared labor that feels like the shape of new trust: not easy, not clean, but promise-shaped and cautious."
    hide maya_ortega
    hide nora_daz
    hide ari_nakamura

    scene bg ch12_f7128a_5 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Swells into a warm fugue; trumpets softened by strings, a clear major chord ringing into the dusk]
    "You close your eyes and breathe the Hub in: the tang of salt, the oil of rope, the laughter and quiet planning. This was the cost you chose—the narrowing of some doors for the expansion of"
    "others. You are not famous. You are not on every stage. But you are needed here in ways that matter with a gravity you can measure by who sleeps under the roof you help keep dry."
    "Nora bumps your shoulder. Samir lifts his mug. Ari Nakamura stands a step away, still a stranger in some ways, but no longer only an adversary. Outside, the marsh breathes, reed-tips trembling silver in the twilight."
    "The legal scaffolding you helped demand will make the neighborhood's future slower and less gilded, but more anchored to the people who belong here."
    show maya_ortega at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_ortega "I will keep tending. I will keep the rituals. We will be slow and stubborn and alive."
    hide maya_ortega

    scene bg ch12_f7128a_6 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Resolves into a calm, open major chord; a soft heart-beat percussion fades to silence]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Distant tide, a final gentle gull cry]
    "You have accepted professional diminishment as the price of keeping what matters: homes, rituals, and the right to shape the shoreline that raises and remembers you. The leak did not give you glory; it gave you"
    "custody of a truth that now has teeth. The city will change; the neighborhood will continue to change with it, under its own terms."
    "You look up at the marsh beyond the Hub and feel a warmth—exhausted, fierce, and sure—spread from your chest down into your hands. This is your work now: slower, underfunded, deeply yours. You would choose it again."

    scene bg ch12_f7128a_7 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A single sustained violin line holds the last note like a promise]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The tide, steady and inevitable]

    scene bg ch12_f7128a_8 at full_bg
    "THE END"
    # [GAME END]
    return
